    <h1>📐 SS1 Technical Drawing: Week 2<br>Drawing Instruments and Materials</h1>
    
    <div class="note">
        <strong>Learning Objectives:</strong> By the end of this lesson, students should be able to identify, state the uses, and describe the care of basic technical drawing instruments and materials.
    </div>

    <h2>1. Drawing Instruments and Materials</h2>
    
    <h3>Overview</h3>
    <p>These are the tools and materials used to produce accurate and neat technical drawings.</p>
    
    <img src="images/drawinginstruments.jpg" alt="Collection of technical drawing instruments">

    <h3>Types of Drawing Instruments</h3>
    
    <h4>A. Measuring & Drawing Tools</h4>
    <ul>
        <li><strong>T-Square</strong> – Used to draw horizontal lines and as a guide for set squares</li>
        <li><strong>Set Squares (45° and 30°/60°)</strong> – Used to draw angles and vertical lines</li>
        <li><strong>Ruler/Scale Rule</strong> – For measuring and drawing straight lines</li>
        <li><strong>Protractor</strong> – For measuring and drawing angles</li>
        <li><strong>Compass</strong> – For drawing circles and arcs</li>
        <li><strong>Divider</strong> – For transferring measurements and dividing lines equally</li>
        <li><strong>French Curves</strong> – For drawing irregular curves</li>
        <li><strong>Flexible Curve</strong> – Bendable tool for custom curves</li>
    </ul>

    <img src="images/tools-labeled.png" alt="Technical drawing tools with labels">

    <h4>B. Drawing Surfaces</h4>
    <ul>
        <li><strong>Drawing Board</strong> – Flat surface to place drawing sheets</li>
        <li><strong>Drawing Table</strong> – Adjustable surface for professional use</li>
    </ul>

    <h4>C. Writing/Marking Instruments</h4>
    <ul>
        <li><strong>Pencils (H, HB, B grades)</strong> – Different hardness for different line weights</li>
        <li><strong>Technical Pens/Rapidograph</strong> – For ink drawings with consistent line width</li>
        <li><strong>Eraser</strong> – For corrections</li>
        <li><strong>Erasing Shield</strong> – Protects surrounding lines when erasing</li>
    </ul>

    <h4>D. Drawing Materials</h4>
    <ul>
        <li><strong>Drawing Paper/Cartridge Paper</strong> – Standard paper for pencil drawings</li>
        <li><strong>Tracing Paper</strong> – Transparent paper for copying drawings</li>
        <li><strong>Drawing Film/Vellum</strong> – Durable, professional drafting material</li>
        <li><strong>Drawing Pins/Clips</strong> – For securing paper to the board</li>
        <li><strong>Masking Tape</strong> – Holds paper without damaging it</li>
    </ul>

    <img src="images/instruments-materials.jpg" alt="Drawing instruments and materials together">

    <h3>Pencil Grades Explained</h3>
    <table>
        <tr><th>Grade</th><th>Type</th><th>Use</th></tr>
        <tr><td>4H – 6H</td><td>Very Hard</td><td>Construction/guide lines</td></tr>
        <tr><td>2H – 3H</td><td>Hard</td><td>Dimension lines</td></tr>
        <tr><td>H</td><td>Medium Hard</td><td>General drawing</td></tr>
        <tr><td>HB</td><td>Medium</td><td>Lettering, sketching</td></tr>
        <tr><td>B – 2B</td><td>Soft</td><td>Artistic shading</td></tr>
    </table>

    <h3>Advantages of Good Instruments</h3>
    <ul>
        <li>Produce accurate, clean drawings</li>
        <li>Increase speed and efficiency</li>
        <li>Improve professional quality</li>
    </ul>

    <h3>Disadvantages</h3>
    <ul>
        <li>Quality instruments can be expensive</li>
        <li>Require maintenance and care</li>
        <li>Some instruments are fragile</li>
    </ul>

    <h2>2. Care and Proper Use of Drawing Instruments</h2>
    
    <h3>Overview</h3>
    <p>Proper care of drawing instruments ensures their longevity, accuracy, and the quality of work produced.</p>

    <h3>Care of Specific Instruments</h3>
    
    <h4>Compass</h4>
    <ul>
        <li>Keep the needle point sharp</li>
        <li>Store in a case to avoid bending</li>
        <li>Do not force the joints — adjust gently</li>
        <li>Replace leads when worn</li>
    </ul>

    <h4>Pencils</h4>
    <ul>
        <li>Sharpen regularly to a fine conical point</li>
        <li>Use a sandpaper block to maintain the point</li>
        <li>Different grades for different line types</li>
    </ul>

    <h4>T-Square & Set Squares</h4>
    <ul>
        <li>Keep edges clean — wipe with a damp cloth</li>
        <li>Store flat to prevent warping</li>
        <li>Never use as a cutting guide (damages edges)</li>
        <li>Check edges for nicks regularly</li>
    </ul>

    <h4>Drawing Board</h4>
    <ul>
        <li>Keep the surface clean and smooth</li>
        <li>Never cut on the drawing board</li>
        <li>Store vertically to prevent warping</li>
    </ul>

    <h4>Technical Pens</h4>
    <ul>
        <li>Clean after use to prevent ink clogging</li>
        <li>Store horizontally or cap tightly</li>
        <li>Use the correct ink type</li>
    </ul>

    <h4>French Curves & Templates</h4>
    <ul>
        <li>Clean ink/graphite after use</li>
        <li>Store flat to prevent bending</li>
    </ul>

    <h3>General Rules of Care</h3>
    <ol>
        <li>Always store instruments in a proper case or box</li>
        <li>Keep all instruments dry — moisture causes rust and damage</li>
        <li>Never drop instruments, especially compasses and pens</li>
        <li>Clean instruments before and after use</li>
        <li>Handle with clean hands to avoid oil transfer to paper</li>
    </ol>

    <h3>Advantages of Proper Care</h3>
    <ul>
        <li>Instruments last longer</li>
        <li>Drawings are more accurate</li>
        <li>Saves money on replacements</li>
        <li>Maintains professional quality</li>
    </ul>

    <h3>Disadvantages of Poor Care</h3>
    <ul>
        <li>Inaccurate drawings</li>
        <li>Damaged instruments</li>
        <li>Increased costs</li>
        <li>Poor-quality output</li>
    </ul>

